				<td class="PanelBodyAlternate"><span class="SmallBoldText">Re: Reconstructed OoW Songlist<a name="70770"/></span><br><span class="SmallText"> Posted: </span><span class="SmallText">Dec 8 04 1:41 PM</span></td>
			</tr><tr>
				<td colspan="2"><span><blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Some are great idea, some are like was posted upgrade we dont really want to see. I dont think we need the HoS upgrade wealready debuff like crazy and i believe the devs are right when they say the amount of debuffage currently in game is much more than enough, almost too much.</span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
Thank you very much, both to you and Treeble for posting
<br />
comments, I really appreciate it.
<br />

<br />
If the amount of debuffage is already too much, then why did both
<br />
chanters and shammy get a cripple upgrade?  Chanters also got a
<br />
new focus effect that reduces aggro on tash by half.  As a known
<br />
debuffing class a new HoS that covers Disease/Poison is the least
<br />
we could ask for.  Plus since it doesn't stack with HoS it can't be
<br />
that bad.
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">Call of the tradewind is a nice attempt for something new, but it lack consistency. Whats the link between agility and beneficial spell ? I also dont think its a good idea to make another Talisman of Sens for us. Its shm stuff, should stay like so. </span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
A tradewind is something both boats and plane use to get a bit
<br />
more bang for their buck.  Even in a football game if you have
<br />
the wind behind you, as a quarterback your throws are going to
<br />
go further.  Right now, other than mana song (most don't even
<br />
know there's an hp regen component) non-nuking casters have
<br />
no reason to want a bard in their group.  Tradewind would give
<br />
shammy/cleric/druid a reason to say &quot;let's get a bard!&quot; so that
<br />
they could get a bit more out of heals.
<br />

<br />
The comment about Talisman of Sense has me a bit confused.
<br />
The song I used that acts in a somewhat similar fashion is
<br />
Verses of Vesargran.  It's actually a song we got in OoW, it is
<br />
just too weak in its current form.  Verses mitigates incoming
<br />
spell and melee damage.  Sense actually increases avoidance
<br />
percentage.  Two different aspect of defense completely.  
<br />
There are other spells that are like Verses of Vesargran, and
<br />
chanters are the ones who got them.  Chanters also got two
<br />
types of new runes to cast on self and group.  Even rangers
<br />
got a new buff that decreases aggro when mob hits you (Ok,
<br />
so rangers also need a lot of help with OoW spells, don't get
<br />
me wrong).  Shammies did not get a new agility upgrade.  They
<br />
can bust the cap on strength, dexterity, and stamina.  So
<br />
getting a new agility buff (we already have agility songs, but
<br />
haven't gotten an upgrade in a long time) seems only natural
<br />
to me, and by breaking the cap it completes the new theme of
<br />
OoW of reaching new highs in all stats.  (as an aside, I believe
<br />
rangers should have received a bust breaking agility buff, with a
<br />
stackable 3-5 percent improved heals component).
<br />

<br />

<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">I also disagree with the AE PoV. Its way too powerful for the first part. On the other hand it destroy bard stackability/desirability on raids, which is already very low. </span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
The new AE resist song will not be as powerful as PoVeeshan
<br />
in the main tank group.  Therefore it will not steal the MT group
<br />
bard's job.  By not being as powerful as a song (or even Veeshan
<br />
+guardian rythmns combo), I don't believe it can be classified as
<br />
way too powerful.  It will stack with either Purifying chorus of
<br />
Elemental chorus, therefore preserving the job of the AE resist
<br />
bard on raids, so I don't believe it reduces bard stackability or
<br />
desirability on raids, but I completely agree that it is already
<br />
very low, and this is one of the songs that I felt addressed that
<br />
problem.
<br />

<br />
One of the roles of bards on raids used to be AE resists.  When
<br />
these songs first came out, the resist caps were 255.  With the
<br />
gear available, most people hovered between 100-150 resists
<br />
with buffs at raids.  Bards would double their current saves, and
<br />
bring them to the cap.  People would blatantly see the difference
<br />
of how many things land on them when a bard is there and when
<br />
one isn't.  People wanted bards at raids, or refused to raid 
<br />
certain targets if bards weren't there to play resists.  With the
<br />
resist caps being 525 (pre AA's) at level 70, playing the old AE
<br />
resist songs nowadays definitely does NOT have the same effect
<br />
it used to.  It's mathematical, the proportion that 140 ish to
<br />
saves when there's a 255 cap, vs. the proportion of 180 ish to
<br />
saves when there's a 525 cap.  Then there's also the factor that
<br />
resist gear used to be hard to come by, whereas nowadays a lot
<br />
of people don't need AE resist songs at all because they already
<br />
are at the cap and see no effect.  I strongly believe that a new
<br />
AE resist song that stacks with the old ones is a very good 
<br />
solution to bring back the role of the AE resist bard on raids.  If
<br />
you compare the ratios now 140/255 vs. 180+180/525(705) it
<br />
seems to me that it's much more in line with what it used to be
<br />
than what it currently is.
<br />

<br />
<blockquote><b>Quote:</b><br><span class="quote">I like the silence component of Bellow of Chaos, i think its your greatest idea on that list. </span></blockquote>
<br />

<br />
We used to get completely off the wall songs that made playing
<br />
a bard unique and fun.  This song was my hommage to that, I
<br />
liken it to DA song or Gate song; a situational song that can be
<br />
very powerful or very useless.  Use sparingly, with a bit of salt!
<br />

<br />
Thanks very much again for your comments, I reallly appreciate
<br />
all the feedback I got so far, and look forward to more 
<br />
comments, whether you agree with me or think I'm an idiot<img src="/skins/default/images/emotions/emotion-2.gif" border="0" alt="Big Smile" hspace="2" /> 
<br />

<br />
'Stuce</span></td>
